==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sad
<hw>Sad</hw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Sadder</adjf>
<pr>(s⟦acr⟧d"d⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Saddest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sad</ets> sated, tired,
satisfied, firm, steadfast, AS. <ets>saed</ets> satisfied, sated; akin
to D. <ets>zat</ets>, OS. <ets>sad</ets>, G. <ets>satt</ets>, OHG.
<ets>sat</ets>, Icel. <ets>sa⟦edh⟧r</ets>, <ets>saddr</ets>, Goth.
<ets>sa⟦thorn⟧s</ets>, Lith. <ets>sotus</ets>, L. <ets>sat</ets>,
<ets>satis</ets>, enough, <ets>satur</ets> sated, Gr.
<grk>'a`menai</grk> to satiate, <grk>'a`dnh</grk> enough. Cf.
<er>Assets</er>, <er>Sate</er>, <er>Satiate</er>, <er>Satisfy</er>,
<er>Satire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Sated; satisfied; weary;
tired.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet of that art they can not waxen <qex>sad</qex>,⟦br⟧
For unto them it is a bitter sweet.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Heavy; weighty; ponderous; close; hard.</def>
<mark>[Obs., except in a few phrases; <as>as, <ex>sad</ex>
bread</as>.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His hand, more <qex>sad</qex> than lump of lead.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chalky lands are naturally cold and <qex>sad</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dull; grave; dark; somber; -- said of colors.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sad</xex>-colored clothes.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Walton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Woad, or wade, is used by the dyers to lay the foundation of all
<qex>sad</qex> colors.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Serious; grave; sober; steadfast; not light or
frivolous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Ripe and <xex>sad</xex>
courage.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lady Catharine, a <qex>sad</qex> and religious woman.</q>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which treaty was wisely handled by <qex>sad</qex> and discrete
counsel of both parties.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Affected with grief or unhappiness; cast down with
affliction; downcast; gloomy; mournful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>First were we <qex>sad</qex>, fearing you would not come;⟦br⟧
Now <qex>sadder</qex>, that you come so unprovided.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The angelic guards ascended, mute and <qex>sad</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Afflictive; calamitous; causing sorrow; <as>as, a
<ex>sad</ex> accident; a <ex>sad</ex> misfortune</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Hence, bad; naughty; troublesome; wicked.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sad</xex> tipsy fellows, both of
them.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Sad</ex> is sometimes used in the formation of
self-explaining compounds; <as>as, <ex>sad</ex>-colored,
<ex>sad</ex>-eyed, <ex>sad</ex>-hearted, <ex>sad</ex>-looking, and the
like</as>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sad bread</b></col>, <cd>heavy bread.</cd> <mark>[Scot. &
Local, U.S.]</mark> <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sorrowful; mournful; gloomy; dejected; depressed;
cheerless; downcast; sedate; serious; grave; grievous; afflictive;
calamitous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sad</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sad
<hw>Sad</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make sorrowful; to sadden.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How it <qex>sadded</qex> the minister's spirits!</q> <rj><qau>H.
Peters.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>SAD</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: SAD
<hw>SAD</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Seasonal affective
disorder.</def> <mark>[Acron.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sadda</ent>⟦br⟧
